From 0000000000000000000000000000000000000000 Mon Sep 17 00:00:00 2001
From: Codex <codex@example.com>
Date: Tue, 30 Jun 2026 11:20:00 +0800
Subject: [PATCH] build: support apparent and canonical label template vars

Kong's template genrule expands placeholders derived from dependency labels.
Some templates use the canonical repository spelling, for example:

  {{@@libexpat//:libexpat}}

With the observed Bazel workspace-mode build, Label stringification can provide
the apparent spelling instead:

  @libexpat//:libexpat

When only one spelling is registered, the placeholder remains unexpanded and
the generated script tries to access a literal path such as
`{{@@libexpat//:libexpat}}/lib/libexpat.*`.

Register both spellings for external and main-repository labels while keeping
the existing template format unchanged.
---
 build/build_system.bzl | 11 ++++++++++-
 1 file changed, 10 insertions(+), 1 deletion(-)

diff --git a/build/build_system.bzl b/build/build_system.bzl
index bfd45d0..6d8d1c2 100644
--- a/build/build_system.bzl
+++ b/build/build_system.bzl
@@ -98,7 +98,16 @@ def _render_template(ctx, output):
             for file in files:  # get the one with shorted path, that will be the directory
                 if len(file.path) < len(p):
                     p = file.path
-        substitutions["{{%s}}" % l.label] = p
+        label = str(l.label)
+        substitutions["{{%s}}" % label] = p
+
+        # Bazel versions differ in whether Label stringification includes the
+        # canonical repository marker ("@@") or the apparent repository marker
+        # ("@"). Keep existing templates working across both forms.
+        if label.startswith("@@"):
+            substitutions["{{%s}}" % label[1:]] = p
+        elif label.startswith("@"):
+            substitutions["{{@%s}}" % label] = p
 
     substitutions["{{CC}}"] = ctx.attr._cc_toolchain[cc_common.CcToolchainInfo].compiler_executable
 
